  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, the activity of money laundering is **prohibited** in virtually every country in the world. It is a serious crime with severe penalties, including imprisonment and hefty fines.\n\nHere's why it's prohibited and some related points:\n\n*   **Undermines the Integrity of Financial Systems:** Money laundering allows criminals to use the legitimate financial system to hide the origins of illicit funds. This can destabilize financial institutions and markets.\n\n*   **Facilitates Criminal Activity:** By cleaning dirty money, money laundering makes it easier for criminals to profit from their illegal activities and continue engaging in them.\n\n*   **Supports Terrorism:** Money laundering can be used to finance terrorist activities, posing a serious threat to national and international security.\n\n*   **International Cooperation:** Due to its cross-border nature, combating money laundering requires strong international cooperation. Numerous international organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), work to set standards and promote effective measures to combat money laundering.\n\n*   **Legal Framework:** Countries have laws in place to criminalize money laundering, require financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs, and cooperate with international efforts to combat money laundering.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is illegal and widely condemned due to its detrimental effects on financial systems, the facilitation of criminal activity, and its potential link to terrorism.",
